01 czerwiec, 2022

Denmark

Denmark : socio-economic indicators 2014 - 2018

The aim of this report is to present the economy and social conditions in 2014 - 2018 .

Our analysis will be divided on four areas using the following variables:

  • economy:
    • GDP per capita
    • Export as GDP percent
    • Import as GDP percent
    • RD as GDP percent - expenses on research and development expressed as % of GDP
  • Population:
    • population
    • birth rate - total number of live births per 1,000 population
    • life expectation by 65
    • life expectation by birth
  • Unemployment:
    • unemployment rate
    • long term unemployment
  • Women situation:
    • fertility rate - total number of children that would be born to each woman if she were to live to the end of her child-bearing years
    • age at 1st child - mean age of women while giving a birth to 1st child
    • gender pay gap - average difference between the remuneration for men and women who are working expressed in %

The dataset was obtained from Eurostat database.

From the table below we can conclude, that the GDP in the period 2014 - 2018 has changed by 13.84%.

Taking into account the change of population by 2.74% such a change in absolute GDP corresponds to change in GDP per capita by 10.81%.

The maximum and minimum export expressed as GDP percent was observed in 2018 and in 2016 respectively.

The maximum and minimum import expressed as GDP percent was observed in 2018 and in 2016 respectively.

Population

Population per Year

The average population between 2014 and 2018 in Denmark was 5.627235^{6}.

The highest population in Denmark was observed in year 2018.

The lowest population in Denmark was observed in year 2014.

Birth rate

The average birth rate between 2014 and 2018 in Denmark was 10.1.

The highest birth rate in Denmark was observed in year 2016.

The lowest birth rate in Denmark was observed in year 2014.
